# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-grid-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Urban distribution is mainly underground, sometimes in common utility ducts.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Rural distribution is mostly above ground with utility poles, and suburban distribution is a mix.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Closer to the customer, a distribution transformer steps the primary distribution power down to a low-voltage secondary circuit, usually 120/240 V in the US for residential customers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The power comes to the customer via a service drop and an electricity meter.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The final circuit in an urban system may be less than 15 metres (50 ft) but may be over 91 metres (300 ft) for a rural customer.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Electric power distribution become necessary only in the 1880s, when electricity started being generated at power stations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Until then, electricity was usually generated where it was used.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The first power-distribution systems installed in European and US cities were used to supply lighting: arc lighting running on very-high-voltage (around 3,000 V) alternating current (AC) or direct current (DC), and incandescent lighting running on low-voltage (100 V) direct current.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Both were supplanting gas lighting systems, with arc lighting taking over large-area and street lighting, and incandescent lighting replacing gas lights for business and residential users.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The high voltages used in arc lighting allowed a single generating station to supply a string of lights up to 7 miles (11 km) long.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] And each doubling of voltage would allow a given cable to transmit the same amount of power four times the distance than at the lower voltage (with the same power loss).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] By contrast, direct-current indoor incandescent lighting systems, such as Edison's first power station, installed in 1882, had difficulty supplying customers more than a mile away because they used a low voltage (110 V) from generation to end use.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The low voltage translated to higher current and required thick copper cables for transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In practice, Edison's DC generating plants needed to be within about 1.5 miles (2.4 km) of the farthest customer to avoid even thicker and more expensive conductors.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The problem of transmitting electricity over longer distances became a recognized engineering roadblock to electric power distribution, with many less-than-satisfactory solutions tested by lighting companies.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] But the mid-1880s saw a breakthrough with the development of functional transformers that allowed AC power to be "stepped up" to a much higher voltage for transmission, then dropped down to a lower voltage near the end user.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Compared to direct current, AC had much cheaper transmission costs and greater economies of scale — with large AC generating plants capable of supplying whole cities and regions, which led to the use of AC spreading rapidly.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Edison's propaganda campaign was short-lived, with his company switching over to AC in 1892.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] AC became the dominant form of transmission of power with innovations in Europe and the US in electric motor designs, and the development of engineered *universal systems* allowing the large number of legacy systems to be connected to large AC grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In the first half of the 20th century, in many places the electric power industry was vertically integrated, meaning that one company did generation, transmission, distribution, metering and billing.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Starting in the 1970s and 1980s, nations began the process of deregulation and privatization, leading to electricity markets.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The distribution system would remain regulated due to being a natural monopoly, but generation, retail, and sometimes transmission systems were transformed into competitive markets.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Electric power begins at a generating station, where the potential difference can be as high as 33,000 volts.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Users of large amounts of DC power such as some railway electrification systems, telephone exchanges and industrial processes such as aluminium smelting use rectifiers to derive DC from the public AC supply, or may have their own generation systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] High-voltage DC can be advantageous for isolating alternating-current systems or controlling the quantity of electricity transmitted.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] For example, Hydro-Québec has a direct-current line which goes from the James Bay region to Boston.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] From the generating station it goes to the generating station's switchyard where a step-up transformer increases the voltage to a level suitable for transmission, from 44 kV to 765 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Once in the transmission system, electricity from each generating station is combined with electricity produced elsewhere.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] For alternating-current generators, all generating units connected to a common network must be synchronized, operating at the same frequency within a small tolerance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Alternatively, disparate sources can be combined to serve a common load if some external power converter, such as a rotating machine or a direct current converter system is interposed.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Electricity is consumed as soon as it is produced.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] It is transmitted at a very high speed, close to the speed of light.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Distribution networks are divided into two types, **radial system** or network.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] A radial system is arranged like a tree where each customer has one source of supply.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] A network system has multiple sources of supply operating in parallel.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Spot networks are used for concentrated loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Radial systems are commonly used in rural or suburban areas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Radial systems usually include emergency connections where the system can be reconfigured in case of problems, such as a fault or planned maintenance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] This can be done by opening and closing switches to isolate a certain section from the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Long feeders experience voltage drop (power factor distortion) requiring capacitors or voltage regulators to be installed.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Reconfiguration, by exchanging the functional links between the elements of the system, represents one of the most important measures which can improve the operational performance of a distribution system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The problem of optimization through the reconfiguration of a power distribution system, in terms of its definition, is a historical single objective problem with constraints.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Since 1975, when Merlin and Back introduced the idea of distribution system reconfiguration for active power loss reduction, until nowadays, a lot of researchers have proposed diverse methods and algorithms to solve the reconfiguration problem as a single objective problem.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Some authors have proposed Pareto optimality based approaches (including active power losses and reliability indices as objectives).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] For this purpose, different artificial intelligence based methods have been used: microgenetic, branch exchange, particle swarm optimization and non-dominated sorting genetic algorithm.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Rural electrification systems tend to use higher distribution voltages because of the longer distances covered by distribution lines (see Rural Electrification Administration).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] 7.2, 12.47, 25, and 34.5 kV distribution is common in the United States; 11 kV and 33 kV are common in the UK, Australia and New Zealand; 11 kV and 22 kV are common in South Africa; 10, 20 and 35 kV are common in China.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Rural services normally try to minimize the number of poles and wires.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] It uses higher voltages (than urban distribution), which in turn permits use of galvanized steel wire.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The strong steel wire allows for less expensive wide pole spacing.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In rural areas a pole-mount transformer may serve only one customer.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In New Zealand, Australia, Saskatchewan, Canada, and South Africa, Single-wire earth return systems (SWER) are used to electrify remote rural areas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Three phase service provides power for large agricultural facilities, petroleum pumping facilities, water plants, or other customers that have large loads (three-phase equipment).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In North America, overhead distribution systems may be three phase, four wire, with a neutral conductor.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Rural distribution system may have long runs of one phase conductor and a neutral.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In other countries or in extreme rural areas the neutral wire is connected to the ground to use that as a return (single-wire earth return).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Electricity is delivered at a frequency of either 50 or 60 Hz, depending on the region.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] It is delivered to domestic customers as single-phase electric power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In some countries as in Europe a three phase supply may be made available for larger properties.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Seen with an oscilloscope, the domestic power supply in North America would look like a sine wave, oscillating between −170 volts and 170 volts, giving an effective voltage of 120 volts RMS.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Three-phase electric power is more efficient in terms of power delivered per cable used, and is more suited to running large electric motors.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Some large European appliances may be powered by three-phase power, such as electric stoves and clothes dryers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] A ground connection is normally provided for the customer's system as well as for the equipment owned by the utility.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The purpose of connecting the customer's system to ground is to limit the voltage that may develop if high voltage conductors fall down onto lower-voltage conductors which are usually mounted lower to the ground, or if a failure occurs within a distribution transformer.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Earthing systems can be TT, TN-S, TN-C-S or TN-C.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Most of the world uses 50 Hz 220 or 230 V single phase, or 380 or 400 V three-phase for residential and light industrial services.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In this system, the primary distribution network supplies a few substations per area, and the 230/400 V power from each substation is directly distributed to end users over a region of normally less than 1 km radius.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Three live (hot) wires and the neutral are connected to the building for a three phase service.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Single-phase distribution, with one live wire and the neutral is used domestically where total loads are light.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In Europe, electricity is normally distributed for industry and domestic use by the three-phase, four wire system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] This gives a phase-to-phase voltage of 400 volts wye service and a single-phase voltage of 230 volts between any one phase and neutral.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In the UK a typical urban or suburban low-voltage substation would normally be rated between 150 kVA and 1 MVA and supply a whole neighbourhood of a few hundred houses.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Transformers are typically sized on an average load of 1 to 2 kW per household, and the service fuses and cable is sized to allow any one property to draw a peak load of perhaps ten times this.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] For industrial customers, 3-phase 400 / 690 volt is also available, or may be generated locally.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Large commercial and industrial customers have their own distribution transformers with an input from 11 kV to 33 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Some high consumption users are supplied by transmission network from 110 kV to 220 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Most of the Americas use 60 Hz AC, the 120/240 volt split-phase system domestically and three phase for larger installations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] North American transformers usually power homes at 240 volts, similar to Europe's 230 volts.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] It is the split-phase that allows use of 120 volts in the home.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] In the electricity sector in Japan, the standard voltage is 100 V, with both 50 and 60 Hz AC frequencies being used.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Parts of the country use 50 Hz, while other parts use 60 Hz.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Some local providers in Tokyo imported 50 Hz German equipment, while the local power providers in Osaka brought in 60 Hz generators from the United States.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The grids grew until eventually the entire country was wired.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Today the frequency is 50 Hz in Eastern Japan (including Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, and Hokkaido) and 60 Hz in Western Japan (including Nagoya, Osaka, Kyoto, Hiroshima, Shikoku, and Kyushu).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Most household appliances are made to work on either frequency.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The problem of incompatibility came into the public eye when the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami knocked out about a third of the east's capacity, and power in the west could not be fully shared with the east since the country does not have a common frequency.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] There are four high-voltage direct current (HVDC) converter stations that move power across Japan's AC frequency border.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Shin Shinano is a back-to-back HVDC facility in Japan which forms one of four frequency changer stations that link Japan's western and eastern power grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The other three are at Higashi-Shimizu, Minami-Fukumitsu and Sakuma Dam.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Together they can move up to 1.2 GW of power east or west.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Most modern North American homes are wired to receive 240 volts from the transformer, and through the use of split-phase electrical power, can have both 120 volt receptacles and 240 volt receptacles.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The 120 volts is typically used for lighting and most wall outlets.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The 240 volt circuits are typically used for appliances requiring high watt heat output such as ovens and heaters.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] They may also be used to supply an electric car charger.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Traditionally, the distribution systems would only operate as simple distribution lines where the electricity from the transmission networks would be shared among the customers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Today's distribution systems are heavily integrated with renewable energy generations at the distribution level of the power systems by the means of distributed generation resources, such as solar power and wind power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] As a result, distribution systems are gradually becoming more independent from the transmission networks.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Balancing the supply-demand relationship at these modern distribution networks (sometimes referred to as microgrids) is challenging, and it requires the use of various economic, technological and operational means to operate.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Such tools include market signals, battery storage power station, data analytics, optimization tools, etc.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] Increased ambient temperatures during extreme heat events can reduce the efficiency of electrical transmission and distribution systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-distribution] The power rating of transformers, underground cables and overhead lines are limited under high ambient temperatures.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines transmit either alternating current (AC) or direct current (DC).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] To increase the efficiency of long-distance electric power transmission, the voltage is often increased for transmission, then reduced for local distribution.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is because higher voltages corresponds to lower currents and lower losses caused by such currents.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The AC voltage level is often changed with transformers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A wide area synchronous grid, known as an *interconnection* in North America, directly connects generators delivering AC power with the same relative *frequency* to many consumers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] North America has four major interconnections: Western, Eastern, Quebec and Texas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] One grid connects most of continental Europe.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were often owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that led to separate companies handling transmission and distribution.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Most North American transmission lines are high-voltage three-phase AC, although single phase AC is sometimes used in railway electrification systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC technology is used for greater efficiency over longer distances, typically hundreds of miles.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) technology is also used in submarine power cables (typically longer than 30 miles (50 km)), and in the interchange of power between grids that are not mutually synchronized.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links stabilize power distribution networks where sudden new loads, or blackouts, in one part of a network might otherwise result in synchronization problems and cascading failures.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity is transmitted at high voltages to reduce the energy loss due to resistance that occurs over long distances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power is usually transmitted through overhead power lines.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground power transmission has a significantly higher installation cost and greater operational limitations, but lowers maintenance costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground transmission is more common in urban areas or visually sensitive locations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electrical energy must typically be generated at the same rate at which it is consumed.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A sophisticated control system is required to ensure that power generation closely matches demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] If demand exceeds supply, the imbalance can cause generation plant(s) and transmission equipment to automatically disconnect or shut down to prevent damage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the worst case, this may lead to a cascading series of shutdowns and a major regional blackout.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The US Northeast faced blackouts in 1965, 1977, 2003, and major blackouts in other US regions in 1996 and 2011.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric transmission networks are interconnected into regional, national, and even continent-wide networks to reduce the risk of such a failure by providing multiple redundant, alternative routes for power to flow should such shutdowns occur.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission companies determine the maximum reliable capacity of each line (ordinarily less than its physical or thermal limit) to ensure that spare capacity is available in the event of a failure in another part of the network.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor consists of seven strands of steel surrounded by four layers of aluminium.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage overhead conductors are not covered by insulation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor material is usually an aluminium alloy, formed of several strands and possibly reinforced with steel strands.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Copper was sometimes used for overhead transmission, but aluminum is lighter, reduces yields only marginally and costs much less.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead conductors are supplied by several companies.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor material and shapes are regularly improved to increase capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor sizes range from 12 mm2 (#6 American wire gauge) to 1,092 mm2 (2,156,000 circular mils area), with varying resistance and current-carrying capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For large conductors (more than a few centimetres in diameter), much of the current flow is concentrated near the surface due to the skin effect.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The center of the conductor carries little current but contributes weight and cost.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, multiple parallel cables (called bundle conductors) are used for higher capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Bundle conductors are used at high voltages to reduce energy loss caused by corona discharge.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Today, transmission-level voltages are usually considered to be 110 kV and above.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lower voltages, such as 66 kV and 33 kV, are usually considered subtransmission voltages, but are occasionally used on long lines with light loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages less than 33 kV are usually used for distribution.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages above 765 kV are considered extra high voltage and require different designs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Increased ambient temperatures during extreme heat events can reduce the efficiency of electrical transmission and distribution, especially in overhead systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thermal expansion causes overhead lines to sag, reducing current flow and increasing the risk of unintended arc discharge if there is vegetation nearby.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead transmission wires depend on air for insulation, requiring that lines maintain minimum clearances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adverse weather conditions, such as high winds and low temperatures, interrupt transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind speeds as low as 23 knots (43 km/h) can permit conductors to encroach operating clearances, resulting in a flashover and loss of supply.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Oscillatory motion of the physical line is termed conductor gallop or flutter depending on the frequency and amplitude of oscillation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric power can be transmitted by underground power cables.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground cables take up no right-of-way, have lower visibility, and are less affected by weather.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Cable and excavation costs are much higher than overhead construction.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Faults in buried transmission lines take longer to locate and repair.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In some metropolitan areas, cables are enclosed by metal pipe and insulated with dielectric fluid (usually an oil) that is either static or circulated via pumps.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] If an electric fault damages the pipe and leaks dielectric, liquid nitrogen is used to freeze portions of the pipe to enable draining and repair.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This extends the repair period and increases costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The temperature of the pipe and surroundings are monitored throughout the repair period.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground lines are limited by their thermal capacity, which permits less overload or re-rating lines.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long underground AC cables have significant capacitance, which reduces their ability to provide useful power beyond 50 miles (80 kilometres).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC cables are not limited in length by their capacitance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Commercial electric power was initially transmitted at the same voltage used by lighting and mechanical loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This restricted the distance between generating plant and loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1882, DC voltage could not easily be increased for long-distance transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Different classes of loads (for example, lighting, fixed motors, and traction/railway systems) required different voltages, and so used different generators and circuits.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, generators were sited near their loads, a practice that later became known as distributed generation using large numbers of small generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission of alternating current (AC) became possible after Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs built what they called the secondary generator, an early transformer provided with 1:1 turn ratio and open magnetic circuit, in 1881.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first long distance AC line was 34 kilometres (21 miles) long, built for the 1884 International Exhibition of Electricity in Turin, Italy.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a 2 kV, 130 Hz Siemens & Halske alternator and featured several Gaulard transformers with primary windings connected in series, which fed incandescent lamps.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The system proved the feasibility of AC electric power transmission over long distances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first commercial AC distribution system entered service in 1885 in via dei Cerchi, Rome, Italy, for public lighting.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by two Siemens & Halske alternators rated 30 hp (22 kW), 2 kV at 120 Hz and used 19 km of cables and 200 parallel-connected 2 kV to 20 V step-down transformers provided with a closed magnetic circuit, one for each lamp.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A few months later it was followed by the first British AC system, serving Grosvenor Gallery.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It also featured Siemens alternators and 2.4 kV to 100 V step-down transformers – one per user – with shunt-connected primaries.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working to improve what he considered an impractical Gaulard-Gibbs design, electrical engineer William Stanley, Jr. developed the first practical series AC transformer in 1885.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working with the support of George Westinghouse, in 1886 he demonstrated a transformer-based AC lighting system in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a steam engine-driven 500 V Siemens generator.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage was stepped down to 100 volts using the Stanley transformer to power incandescent lamps at 23 businesses over 4,000 feet (1,200 m).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This practical demonstration of a transformer and alternating current lighting system led Westinghouse to begin installing AC systems later that year.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1888 the first designs for an AC motor appeared.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These were induction motors running on polyphase current, independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Practical three-phase motors were designed by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Widespread use of such motors were delayed many years by development problems and the scarcity of polyphase power systems needed to power them.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the late 1880s and early 1890s smaller electric companies merged into larger corporations such as Ganz and AEG in Europe and General Electric and Westinghouse Electric in the US.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These companies developed AC systems, but the technical difference between direct and alternating current systems required a much longer technical merger.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Alternating current's economies of scale with large generating plants and long-distance transmission slowly added the ability to link all the loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These included single phase AC systems, poly-phase AC systems, low voltage incandescent lighting, high-voltage arc lighting, and existing DC motors in factories and street cars.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In what became a universal system, these technological differences were temporarily bridged via the rotary converters and motor-generators that allowed the legacy systems to connect to the AC grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These stopgaps were slowly replaced as older systems were retired or upgraded.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first transmission of single-phase alternating current using high voltage came in Oregon in 1890 when power was delivered from a hydroelectric plant at Willamette Falls to the city of Portland 14 miles (23 km) down river.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first three-phase alternating current using high voltage took place in 1891 during the international electricity exhibition in Frankfurt.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 15 kV transmission line, approximately 175 km long, connected Lauffen on the Neckar and Frankfurt.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission voltages increased throughout the 20th century.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] By 1914, fifty-five transmission systems operating at more than 70 kV were in service.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The highest voltage then used was 150 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnecting multiple generating plants over a wide area reduced costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The most efficient plants could be used to supply varying loads during the day.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reliability was improved and capital costs were reduced, because stand-by generating capacity could be shared over many more customers and a wider area.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Remote and low-cost sources of energy, such as hydroelectric power or mine-mouth coal, could be exploited to further lower costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 20th century's rapid industrialization made electrical transmission lines and grids critical infrastructure.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnection of local generation plants and small distribution networks was spurred by World War I, when large electrical generating plants were built by governments to power munitions factories.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These networks use components such as power lines, cables, circuit breakers, switches and transformers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission network is usually administered on a regional basis by an entity such as a regional transmission organization or transmission system operator.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission efficiency is improved at higher voltage and lower current.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The reduced current reduces heating losses.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Joule's first law states that energy losses are proportional to the square of the current.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, reducing the current by a factor of two lowers the energy lost to conductor resistance by a factor of four for any given size of conductor.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The optimum size of a conductor for a given voltage and current can be estimated by Kelvin's law for conductor size, which states that size is optimal when the annual cost of energy wasted in resistance is equal to the annual capital charges of providing the conductor.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] At times of lower interest rates and low commodity costs, Kelvin's law indicates that thicker wires are optimal.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Otherwise, thinner conductors are indicated.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since power lines are designed for long-term use, Kelvin's law is used in conjunction with long-term estimates of the price of copper and aluminum as well as interest rates.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher voltage is achieved in AC circuits by using a *step-up transformer*.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) systems require relatively costly conversion equipment that may be economically justified for particular projects such as submarine cables and longer distance high capacity point-to-point transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is necessary for sending energy between unsynchronized grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A transmission grid is a network of power stations, transmission lines, and substations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Energy is usually transmitted within a grid with three-phase AC.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Single-phase AC is used only for distribution to end users since it is not usable for large polyphase induction motors.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the 19th century, two-phase transmission was used but required either four wires or three wires with unequal currents.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher order phase systems require more than three wires, but deliver little or no benefit.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] While the price of generating capacity is high, energy demand is variable, making it often cheaper to import needed power than to generate it locally.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because loads often rise and fall together across large areas, power often comes from distant sources.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of the economic benefits of load sharing, wide area transmission grids may span countries and even continents.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnections between producers and consumers enables power to flow even if some links are inoperative.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The slowly varying portion of demand is known as the *base load* and is generally served by large facilities with constant operating costs, termed firm power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such facilities are nuclear, coal or hydroelectric, while other energy sources such as concentrated solar thermal and geothermal power have the potential to provide firm power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Renewable energy sources, such as solar photovoltaics, wind, wave, and tidal, are, due to their intermittency, not considered to be firm.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The remaining or *peak* power demand, is supplied by peaking power plants, which are typically smaller, faster-responding, and higher cost sources, such as combined cycle or combustion turbine plants typically fueled by natural gas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] New York often buys over 1000 MW of low-cost hydropower from Canada.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Local sources (even if more expensive and infrequently used) can protect the power supply from weather and other disasters that can disconnect distant suppliers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Hydro and wind sources cannot be moved closer to big cities, and solar costs are lowest in remote areas where local power needs are nominal.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Connection costs can determine whether any particular renewable alternative is economically realistic.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Costs can be prohibitive for transmission lines, but high capacity, long distance super grid transmission network costs could be recovered with modest usage fees.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] At power stations, power is produced at a relatively low voltage between about 480 V and 22 kV, depending on the size of the unit.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage is then stepped up by the power station transformer to a higher voltage (100 kV to 1,000 kV AC) for transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, power transmission is, variously, 230 kV to 500 kV, with less than 230 kV or more than 500 kV as exceptions.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Western Interconnection has two primary interchange voltages: 500 kV AC at 60 Hz, and ±500 kV (1,000 kV net) DC from North to South (Columbia River to Southern California) and Northeast to Southwest (Utah to Southern California).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 287.5 kV (Hoover Dam to Los Angeles line, via Victorville) and 345 kV (Arizona Public Service (APS) line) are local standards, both of which were implemented before 500 kV became practical.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmitting electricity at high voltage reduces the fraction of energy lost to Joule heating, which varies by conductor type, the current, and the transmission distance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, a 100 miles (160 km) span at 765 kV carrying 1000 MW of power can have losses of 0.5% to 1.1%.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 345 kV line carrying the same load across the same distance has losses of 4.2%.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a given amount of power, a higher voltage reduces the current and thus the resistive losses.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, raising the voltage by a factor of 10 reduces the current by a corresponding factor of 10 and therefore the $I^{2}R$ losses by a factor of 100, provided the same sized conductors are used in both cases.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Even if the conductor size (cross-sectional area) is decreased ten-fold to match the lower current, the $I^{2}R$ losses are still reduced ten-fold using the higher voltage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] While power loss can also be reduced by increasing the wire's conductance (by increasing its cross-sectional area), larger conductors are heavier and more expensive.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] And since conductance is proportional to cross-sectional area, resistive power loss is only reduced proportionally with increasing cross-sectional area, providing a much smaller benefit than the squared reduction provided by multiplying the voltage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long-distance transmission is typically done with overhead lines at voltages of 115 to 1,200 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] At higher voltages, where more than 2,000 kV exists between conductor and ground, corona discharge losses are so large that they can offset the lower resistive losses in the line conductors.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Measures to reduce corona losses include larger conductor diameter, hollow cores or conductor bundles.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Factors that affect resistance and thus loss include temperature, spiraling, and the skin effect.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spiraling, which refers to the way stranded conductors spiral about the center, also contributes to increases in conductor resistance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The skin effect causes the effective resistance to increase at higher AC frequencies.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Corona and resistive losses can be estimated using a mathematical model.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] US transmission and distribution losses were estimated at 6.6% in 1997, 6.5% in 2007 and 5% from 2013 to 2019.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In general, losses are estimated from the discrepancy between power produced (as reported by power plants) and power sold; the difference constitutes transmission and distribution losses, assuming no utility theft occurs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 1980, the longest cost-effective distance for DC transmission was 7,000 kilometres (4,300 miles).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For AC it was 4,000 kilometres (2,500 miles), though US transmission lines are substantially shorter.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In any AC line, conductor inductance and capacitance can be significant.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Currents that flow solely in reaction to these properties, (which together with the resistance define the impedance) constitute reactive power flow, which transmits no power to the load.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These reactive currents, however, cause extra heating losses.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The ratio of real power transmitted to the load to apparent power (the product of a circuit's voltage and current, without reference to phase angle) is the power factor.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] As reactive current increases, reactive power increases and power factor decreases.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For transmission systems with low power factor, losses are higher than for systems with high power factor.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Utilities add capacitor banks, reactors and other components (such as phase-shifters; static VAR compensators; and flexible AC transmission systems, FACTS) throughout the system help to compensate for the reactive power flow, reduce the losses in power transmission and stabilize system voltages.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These measures are collectively called 'reactive support'.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Current flowing through transmission lines induces a magnetic field that surrounds the lines of each phase and affects the inductance of the surrounding conductors of other phases.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductors' mutual inductance is partially dependent on the physical orientation of the lines with respect to each other.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Three-phase lines are conventionally strung with phases separated vertically.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The mutual inductance seen by a conductor of the phase in the middle of the other two phases is different from the inductance seen on the top/bottom.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Unbalanced inductance among the three conductors is problematic because it may force the middle line to carry a disproportionate amount of the total power transmitted.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Similarly, an unbalanced load may occur if one line is consistently closest to the ground and operates at a lower impedance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of this phenomenon, conductors must be periodically transposed along the line so that each phase sees equal time in each relative position to balance out the mutual inductance seen by all three phases.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] To accomplish this, line position is swapped at specially designed transposition towers at regular intervals along the line using various transposition schemes.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission runs at relatively lower voltages.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is uneconomical to connect all distribution substations to the high main transmission voltage, because that equipment is larger and more expensive.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Typically, only larger substations connect with this high voltage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage is stepped down before the current is sent to smaller substations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission circuits are usually arranged in loops so that a single line failure does not stop service to many customers for more than a short time.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Loops can be *normally closed*, where loss of one circuit should result in no interruption, or *normally open* where substations can switch to a backup supply.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] While subtransmission circuits are usually carried on overhead lines, in urban areas buried cable may be used.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lower-voltage subtransmission lines use less right-of-way and simpler structures; undergrounding is less difficult.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] No fixed cutoff separates subtransmission and transmission, or subtransmission and distribution.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages of 69 kV, 115 kV, and 138 kV are often used for subtransmission in North America.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] As power systems evolved, voltages formerly used for transmission were used for subtransmission, and subtransmission voltages became distribution voltages.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Like transmission, subtransmission moves relatively large amounts of power, and like distribution, subtransmission covers an area instead of just point-to-point.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Substation transformers reduce the voltage to a lower level for distribution to customers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This distribution is accomplished with a combination of sub-transmission (33 to 138 kV) and distribution (3.3 to 25 kV).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Finally, at the point of use, the energy is transformed to end-user voltage (100 to 4160 volts).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage power transmission allows for lesser resistive losses over long distances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This efficiency delivers a larger proportion of the generated power to the loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In a simplified model, the grid delivers electricity from an ideal voltage source with voltage V , delivering a power $P_{V}$ ) to a single point of consumption, modelled by a resistance R , when the wires are long enough to have a significant resistance $R_{C}$ .
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] If the resistances are in series with no intervening transformer, the circuit acts as a voltage divider, because the same current $I={\frac {V}{R+R_{C}}}$ runs through the wire resistance and the powered device.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For $a>1$ (i.e. conversion of high voltage to low voltage near the consumption point), a larger fraction of the generator's power is transmitted to the consumption point and a lesser fraction is lost to Joule heating.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The terminal characteristics of the transmission line are the voltage and current at the sending (S) and receiving (R) ends.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The line is assumed to be a reciprocal, symmetrical network, meaning that the receiving and sending labels can be switched with no consequence.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The parameters *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D* differ depending on how the desired model handles the line's resistance (*R*), inductance (*L*), capacitance (*C*), and shunt (parallel, leak) conductance *G*.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The four main models are the short line approximation, the medium line approximation, the long line approximation (with distributed parameters), and the lossless line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In such models, a capital letter such as *R* refers to the total quantity summed over the line and a lowercase letter such as *c* refers to the per-unit-length quantity.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lossless line approximation is the least accurate; it is typically used on short lines where the inductance is much greater than the resistance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For this approximation, the voltage and current are identical at the sending and receiving ends.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The characteristic impedance is pure real, which means resistive for that impedance, and it is often called surge impedance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] When a lossless line is terminated by surge impedance, the voltage does not drop.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Though the phase angles of voltage and current are rotated, the magnitudes of voltage and current remain constant along the line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load > SIL, the voltage drops from sending end and the line *consumes* VARs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load < SIL, the voltage increases from the sending end, and the line *generates* VARs.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The short line approximation is normally used for lines shorter than 80 km (50 mi).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] There, only a series impedance *Z* is considered, while *C* and *G* are ignored.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The final result is that A = D = 1 per unit, B = Z Ohms, and C = 0.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The medium line approximation is used for lines running between 80 and 250 km (50 and 155 mi).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The series impedance and the shunt (current leak) conductance are considered, placing half of the shunt conductance at each end of the line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This circuit is often referred to as a *nominal *π* (pi)* circuit because of the shape (*π*) that is taken on when leak conductance is placed on both sides of the circuit diagram.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The long line model is used when a higher degree of accuracy is needed or when the line under consideration is more than 250 km (160 mi) long.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series resistance and shunt conductance are considered to be distributed parameters, such that each differential length of the line has a corresponding differential series impedance and shunt admittance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The following result can be applied at any point along the transmission line, where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] To find the voltage and current at the end of the long line, x should be replaced with l (the line length) in all parameters of the transmission matrix.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This model applies the Telegrapher's equations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) is used to transmit large amounts of power over long distances or for interconnections between asynchronous grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] When electrical energy is transmitted over very long distances, the power lost in AC transmission becomes appreciable and it is less expensive to use direct current instead.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a long transmission line, these lower losses (and reduced construction cost of a DC line) can offset the cost of the required converter stations at each end.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is used for long submarine cables where AC cannot be used because of cable capacitance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In these cases special high-voltage cables are used.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Submarine connections up to 600 kilometres (370 mi) in length have been deployed.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links can be used to control grid problems.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power transmitted by an AC line increases as the phase angle between source end voltage and destination ends increases, but too large a phase angle allows the systems at either end to fall out of step.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since the power flow in a DC link is controlled independently of the phases of the AC networks that it connects, this phase angle limit does not exist, and a DC link is always able to transfer its full rated power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A DC link therefore stabilizes the AC grid at either end, since power flow and phase angle can then be controlled independently.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] As an example, to adjust the flow of AC power on a hypothetical line between Seattle and Boston would require adjustment of the relative phase of the two regional electrical grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is an everyday occurrence in AC systems, but one that can become disrupted when AC system components fail and place unexpected loads on the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] (and possibly in other cooperating cities along the transmission route).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such a system could be less prone to failure if parts of it were suddenly shut down.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] One example of a long DC transmission line is the Pacific DC Intertie located in the Western United States.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The amount of power that can be sent over a transmission line varies with the length of the line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The heating of short line conductors due to line losses sets a thermal limit.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] If too much current is drawn, conductors may sag too close to the ground, or conductors and equipment may overheat.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For intermediate-length lines on the order of 100 kilometres (62 miles), the limit is set by the voltage drop in the line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For longer AC lines, system stability becomes the limiting factor.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Approximately, the power flowing over an AC line is proportional to the cosine of the phase angle of the voltage and current at the ends.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This angle varies depending on system loading.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is undesirable for the angle to approach 90 degrees, as the power flowing decreases while resistive losses remain.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The product of line length and maximum load is approximately proportional to the square of the system voltage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series capacitors or phase-shifting transformers are used on long lines to improve stability.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC lines are restricted only by thermal and voltage drop limits, since the phase angle is not material.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Understanding the temperature distribution along the cable route became possible with the introduction of distributed temperature sensing (DTS) systems that measure temperatures all along the cable.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Without them maximum current was typically set as a compromise between understanding of operation conditions and risk minimization.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This monitoring solution uses passive optical fibers as temperature sensors, either inside a high-voltage cable or externally mounted on the cable insulation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] For overhead cables the fiber is integrated into the core of a phase wire.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The integrated Dynamic Cable Rating (DCR)/Real Time Thermal Rating (RTTR) solution makes it possible to run the network to its maximum.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] It allows the operator to predict the behavior of the transmission system to reflect major changes to its initial operating conditions.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some utilities have embraced reconductoring to handle the increase in electricity production.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring is the replacement-in-place of existing transmission lines with higher-capacity lines.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adding transmission lines is difficult due to cost, permit intervals, and local opposition.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring has the potential to double the amount of electricity that can travel across a transmission line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 2024 report found the United States behind countries like Belgium and the Netherlands in adoption of this technique to accommodate electrification and renewable energy.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In April 2022, the Biden Administration streamlined environmental reviews for such projects, and in May 2022 announced competitive grants for them funded by the 2021 Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and 2022 Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The rate of transmission expansion needs to double to support ongoing electrification and reach emission reduction targets.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 2022, more than 10,000 power plant and energy storage projects were awaiting permission to connect to the US grid — 95% were zero-carbon resources.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] New power lines can take 10 years to plan, permit, and build.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Traditional power lines use a steel core surrounded by aluminum strands (Aluminium-conductor steel-reinforced cable).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Replacing the steel with a lighter, stronger composite material such as carbon fiber (ACCC conductor) allows lines to operate at higher temperatures, with less sag, and doubled transmission capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lowering line sag at high temperatures can prevent wildfires from starting when power lines touch dry vegetation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Although advanced lines can cost 2-4x more than steel, total reconductoring costs are less than half of a new line, given savings in time, land acquisition, permitting, and construction.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A reconductoring project in southeastern Texas upgraded 240 miles of transmission lines at a cost of $900,000 per mile, versus a 3,600-mile greenfield project that averaged $1.9 million per mile.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] To ensure safe and predictable operation, system components are controlled with generators, switches, circuit breakers and loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage, power, frequency, load factor, and reliability capabilities of the transmission system are designed to provide cost effective performance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system provides for base load and peak load capability, with margins for safety and fault tolerance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Peak load times vary by region largely due to the industry mix.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In hot and cold climates home air conditioning and heating loads affect the overall load.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] They are typically highest in the late afternoon in the hottest part of the year and in mid-mornings and mid-evenings in the coldest part of the year.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power requirements vary by season and time of day.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Distribution system designs always take the base load and the peak load into consideration.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system usually does not have a large buffering capability to match loads with generation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus generation has to be kept matched to the load, to prevent overloading generation equipment.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Multiple sources and loads can be connected to the transmission system and they must be controlled to provide orderly transfer of power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In centralized power generation, only local control of generation is necessary.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This involves synchronization of the generation units.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In distributed power generation the generators are geographically distributed and the process to bring them online and offline must be carefully controlled.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The load control signals can either be sent on separate lines or on the power lines themselves.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage and frequency can be used as signaling mechanisms to balance the loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In voltage signaling, voltage is varied to increase generation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power added by any system increases as the line voltage decreases.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This arrangement is stable in principle.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage-based regulation is complex to use in mesh networks, since the individual components and setpoints would need to be reconfigured every time a new generator is added to the mesh.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In frequency signaling, the generating units match the frequency of the power transmission system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In droop speed control, if the frequency decreases, the power is increased.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind turbines, vehicle-to-grid, virtual power plants, and other locally distributed storage and generation systems can interact with the grid to improve system operation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Internationally, a slow move from a centralized to decentralized power systems have taken place.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The main draw of locally distributed generation systems is that they reduce transmission losses by leading to consumption of electricity closer to where it was produced.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Under excess load conditions, the system can be designed to fail incrementally rather than all at once.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Brownouts occur when power supplied drops below the demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Blackouts occur when the grid fails completely.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rolling blackouts (also called load shedding) are intentionally engineered electrical power outages, used to distribute insufficient power to various loads in turn.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Grid operators require reliable communications to manage the grid and associated generation and distribution facilities.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Fault-sensing protective relays at each end of the line must communicate to monitor the flow of power so that faulted conductors or equipment can be quickly de-energized and the balance of the system restored.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Protection of the transmission line from short circuits and other faults is usually so critical that common carrier telecommunications are insufficiently reliable, while in some remote areas no common carrier is available.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rarely, and for short distances, pilot-wires are strung along the transmission line path.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Leased circuits from common carriers are not preferred since availability is not under control of the operator.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines can be used to carry data: this is called power-line carrier, or power-line communication (PLC).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] PLC signals can be easily received with a radio in the long wave range.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Optical fibers can be included in the stranded conductors of a transmission line, in the overhead shield wires.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These cables are known as optical ground wire (*OPGW*).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Sometimes a standalone cable is used, all-dielectric self-supporting (*ADSS*) cable, attached to the transmission line cross arms.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some jurisdictions, such as Minnesota, prohibit energy transmission companies from selling surplus communication bandwidth or acting as a telecommunications common carrier.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Where the regulatory structure permits, the utility can sell capacity in extra dark fibers to a common carrier.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity transmission is generally considered to be a natural monopoly, but one that is not inherently linked to generation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Many countries regulate transmission separately from generation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain was the first country to establish a regional transmission organization.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In that country, transmission operations and electricity markets are separate.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system operator is Red Eléctrica de España (REE) and the wholesale electricity market operator is Operador del Mercado Ibérico de Energía – Polo Español, S.A.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain's transmission system is interconnected with those of France, Portugal, and Morocco.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The establishment of RTOs in the United States was spurred by the FERC's Order 888, *Promoting Wholesale Competition Through Open Access Non-discriminatory Transmission Services by Public Utilities; Recovery of Stranded Costs by Public Utilities and Transmitting Utilities*, issued in 1996.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States and parts of Canada, electric transmission companies operate independently of generation companies, but in the Southern United States vertical integration is intact.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In regions of separation, transmission owners and generation owners continue to interact with each other as market participants with voting rights within their RTO.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] RTOs in the United States are regulated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Merchant transmission projects in the United States include the Cross Sound Cable from Shoreham, New York to New Haven, Connecticut, Neptune RTS Transmission Line from Sayreville, New Jersey, to New Bridge, New York, and Path 15 in California.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Additional projects are in development or have been proposed throughout the United States, including the Lake Erie Connector, an underwater transmission line proposed by ITC Holdings Corp., connecting Ontario to load serving entities in the PJM Interconnection region.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Australia has one unregulated or market interconnector – Basslink – between Tasmania and Victoria.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Two DC links originally implemented as market interconnectors, Directlink and Murraylink, were converted to regulated interconnectors.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A major barrier to wider adoption of merchant transmission is the difficulty in identifying who benefits from the facility so that the beneficiaries pay the toll.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Also, it is difficult for a merchant transmission line to compete when the alternative transmission lines are subsidized by utilities with a monopolized and regulated rate base.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, the FERC's Order 1000, issued in 2010, attempted to reduce barriers to third party investment and creation of merchant transmission lines where a public policy need is found.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The cost of high voltage transmission is comparatively low, compared to all other costs constituting consumer electricity bills.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the UK, transmission costs are about 0.2 p per kWh compared to a delivered domestic price of around 10 p per kWh.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The level of capital expenditure in the electric power T&D equipment market was estimated to be $128.9 bn in 2011.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Mainstream scientific evidence suggests that low-power, low-frequency, electromagnetic radiation associated with household currents and high transmission power lines does not constitute a short- or long-term health hazard.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some studies failed to find any link between living near power lines and developing any sickness or diseases, such as cancer.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 1997 study reported no increased risk of cancer or illness from living near a transmission line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Other studies, however, reported statistical correlations between various diseases and living or working near power lines.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] No adverse health effects have been substantiated for people not living close to power lines.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The New York State Public Service Commission conducted a study to evaluate potential health effects of electric fields.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The study measured the electric field strength at the edge of an existing right-of-way on a 765 kV transmission line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The field strength was 1.6 kV/m, and became the interim maximum strength standard for new transmission lines in New York State.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The opinion also limited the voltage of new transmission lines built in New York to 345 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] On September 11, 1990, after a similar study of magnetic field strengths, the NYSPSC issued their *Interim Policy Statement on Magnetic Fields*.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] This policy established a magnetic field standard of 200 mG at the edge of the right-of-way using the winter-normal conductor rating.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] As a comparison with everyday items, a hair dryer or electric blanket produces a 100 mG – 500 mG magnetic field.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Applications for a new transmission line typically include an analysis of electric and magnetic field levels at the edge of rights-of-way.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Public utility commissions typically do not comment on health impacts.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Biological effects have been established for acute high level exposure to magnetic fields above 100 μT (1 G) (1,000 mG).
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] These levels exceed average residential power-frequency magnetic fields in homes, which are about 0.07 μT (0.7 mG) in Europe and 0.11 μT (1.1 mG) in North America.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Earth's natural geomagnetic field strength varies over the surface of the planet between 0.035 mT and 0.07 mT (35 μT – 70 μT or 350 mG – 700 mG) while the international standard for continuous exposure is set at 40 mT (400,000 mG or 400 G) for the general public.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p01] Tree growth regulators and herbicides may be used in transmission line right of ways, which may have health effects.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] In some countries where electric locomotives or electric multiple units run on low frequency AC power, separate single phase traction power networks are operated by the railways.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Prime examples are countries such as Austria, Germany and Switzerland that utilize AC technology based on 16 2*/*3 Hz.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Norway and Sweden also use this frequency but use conversion from the 50 Hz public supply; Sweden has a 16 2*/*3 Hz traction grid but only for part of the system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] High-temperature superconductors (HTS) promise to revolutionize power distribution by providing lossless transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] The development of superconductors with transition temperatures higher than the boiling point of liquid nitrogen has made the concept of superconducting power lines commercially feasible, at least for high-load applications.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] It has been estimated that waste would be halved using this method, since the necessary refrigeration equipment would consume about half the power saved by the elimination of resistive losses.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Companies such as Consolidated Edison and American Superconductor began commercial production of such systems in 2007.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Superconducting cables are particularly suited to high load density areas such as the business district of large cities, where purchase of an easement for cables is costly.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return (SWER) or single-wire ground return is a single-wire transmission line for supplying single-phase electrical power to remote areas at low cost.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] It is principally used for rural electrification, but also finds use for larger isolated loads such as water pumps.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return is also used for HVDC over submarine power cables.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Both Nikola Tesla and Hidetsugu Yagi attempted to devise systems for large scale wireless power transmission in the late 1800s and early 1900s, without commercial success.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] In November 2009, LaserMotive won the NASA 2009 Power Beaming Challenge by powering a cable climber 1 km vertically using a ground-based laser transmitter.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] The system produced up to 1 kW of power at the receiver end.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] In August 2010, NASA contracted with private companies to pursue the design of laser power beaming systems to power low earth orbit satellites and to launch rockets using laser power beams.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Wireless power transmission has been studied for transmission of power from solar power satellites to the earth.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] A high power array of microwave or laser transmitters would beam power to a rectenna.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] Major engineering and economic challenges face any solar power satellite project.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] The federal government of the United States stated that the American power grid was susceptible to cyber-warfare.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] The United States Department of Homeland Security works with industry to identify vulnerabilities and to help industry enhance the security of control system networks.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] In June 2019, Russia conceded that it was "possible" its electrical grid is under cyber-attack by the United States.
[src:power-grid-systems/electric-power-transmission-p02] *The New York Times* reported that American hackers from the United States Cyber Command planted malware potentially capable of disrupting the Russian electrical grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] An **electrical grid** (or **electricity network**) is an interconnected network for electricity delivery from producers to consumers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electrical grids consist of power stations, electrical substations to step voltage up or down, electric power transmission to carry power over long distances, and finally electric power distribution to customers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In that last step, voltage is stepped down again to the required service voltage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Power stations are typically built close to energy sources and far from densely populated areas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electrical grids vary in size and can cover whole countries or continents.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] From small to large there are microgrids, wide area synchronous grids, and super grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The combined transmission and distribution network is part of electricity delivery, known as the *power grid*.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Grids are nearly always synchronous, meaning all distribution areas operate with three phase alternating current (AC) frequencies synchronized (so that voltage swings occur at almost the same time).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This allows transmission of AC power throughout the area, connecting the electricity generators with consumers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Grids can enable more efficient electricity markets.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Although electrical grids are widespread, as of 2016, 1.4 billion people worldwide were not connected to an electricity grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] As electrification increases, the number of people with access to grid electricity is growing.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] About 840 million people (mostly in Africa), which is ca.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] 11% of the World's population, had no access to grid electricity in 2017, down from 1.2 billion in 2010.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electrical grids can be prone to malicious intrusion or attack; thus, there is a need for electric grid security.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Also as electric grids modernize and introduce computer technology, cyber threats start to become a security risk.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Particular concerns relate to the more complex computer systems needed to manage grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A microgrid is a local grid that is usually part of the regional wide-area synchronous grid, but which can disconnect and operate autonomously.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] It might do this in times when the main grid is affected by outages.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This is known as islanding, and it might run indefinitely on its own resources.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Compared to larger grids, microgrids typically use a lower voltage distribution network and distributed generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Microgrids may not only be more resilient, but may be cheaper to implement in isolated areas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A design goal is that a local area produces all of the energy it uses.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A *wide area synchronous grid* (also called an "interconnection" in North America) is an electrical grid at a regional scale or greater that operates at a synchronized frequency and is electrically tied together during normal system conditions.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For example, there are four major interconnections in North America (the Western Interconnection, the Eastern Interconnection, the Quebec Interconnection and the Texas Interconnection).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In Europe, one large grid connects most of Western Europe.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] These are also known as synchronous zones, the largest of which is the synchronous grid of Continental Europe (ENTSO-E) with 667 gigawatts (GW) of generation, and the widest region served being that of the IPS/UPS system serving countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Synchronous grids with ample capacity facilitate electricity market trading across wide areas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the ENTSO-E in 2008, over 350,000 megawatt hours were sold per day on the European Energy Exchange (EEX).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Each of the interconnects in North America are run at a nominal 60 Hz, while those of Europe run at 50 Hz.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] One disadvantage of a wide-area synchronous grid is that problems in one part can have repercussions across the whole grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For example, in 2018, Kosovo used more power than it generated due to a dispute with Serbia, leading to the phase across the whole synchronous grid of Continental Europe lagging behind what it should have been.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This caused certain kinds of clocks to become six minutes slow.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A *super grid* or *supergrid* is a wide-area transmission network that is intended to make possible the trade of high volumes of electricity across great distances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] It is sometimes also referred to as a *mega grid*.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Super grids can support a global energy transition by smoothing local fluctuations of wind energy and solar energy.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In this context, they are considered as a key technology to mitigate global warming.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Super grids typically use high-voltage direct current (HVDC) to transmit electricity long distances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The latest generation of HVDC power lines can transmit energy with losses of only 1.6% per 1000 km.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electric utilities between regions are many times interconnected for improved economy and reliability.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electrical interconnectors allow for economies of scale, allowing energy to be purchased from large, efficient sources.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Utilities can draw power from generator reserves from a different region to ensure continuing, reliable power and diversify their loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Interconnection also allows regions to have access to cheap bulk energy by receiving power from different sources.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For example, one region may be producing cheap hydro power during high water seasons, but in low water seasons, another area may be producing cheaper power through wind, allowing both regions to access cheaper energy sources from one another during different times of the year.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Neighboring utilities also help others to maintain the overall system frequency and also help manage tie transfers between utility regions.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electricity Interconnection Level (EIL) of a grid is the ratio of the total interconnector power to the grid divided by the installed production capacity of the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Within the EU, it has set a target of national grids reaching 10% by 2020, and 15% by 2030.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electricity generation is the process of generating electric power at power stations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This is done ultimately from sources of primary energy typically with electromechanical generators driven by heat engines from fossil, nuclear, and geothermal sources, or driven by the kinetic energy of water or wind.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Other power sources are photovoltaics driven by solar insolation, and grid batteries.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The sum of the power outputs of generators on the grid is the production of the grid, typically measured in gigawatts (GW).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electric power transmission is the bulk movement of electrical energy from a generating site, via a web of interconnected lines, to an electrical substation, from which is connected to the distribution system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This networked system of connections is distinct from the local wiring between high-voltage substations and customers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Transmission networks are built with redundant pathways to prevent a single point of failure.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In case of line failures this redundancy allows power to be simply rerouted while repairs are done.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Because the power is often generated far from where it is consumed, the transmission system can cover great distances.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For a given amount of power, transmission efficiency is greater at higher voltages and lower currents.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Therefore, voltages are stepped up at the generating station, and stepped down at local substations for distribution to customers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Three-phase, compared to single-phase, can deliver much more power for a given amount of wire, since the neutral and ground wires are shared.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Further, three-phase generators and motors are more efficient than their single-phase counterparts.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] However, for conventional conductors one of the main losses are resistive losses which are a square law on current, and depend on distance.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] High voltage AC transmission lines can lose 1–4% per hundred miles.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] However, high-voltage direct current can have half the losses of AC.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Over very long distances, these efficiencies can offset the additional cost of the required AC/DC converter stations at each end.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Substations may perform many different functions but usually transform voltage from low to high (step up) and from high to low (step down).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Between the generator and the final consumer, the voltage may be transformed several times.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Distribution is the final stage in the delivery of power; it carries electricity from the transmission system to individual consumers.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Substations connect to the transmission system and lower the transmission voltage to medium voltage ranging between 2 kV and 35 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] But the voltage levels varies very much between different countries, in Sweden medium voltage are normally 10 kV between 20 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Primary distribution lines carry this medium voltage power to distribution transformers located near the customer's premises.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Distribution transformers again lower the voltage to the utilization voltage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Customers demanding a much larger amount of power may be connected directly to the primary distribution level or the subtransmission level.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Distribution networks are divided into two types, radial or network.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In cities and towns of North America, the grid tends to follow the classic *radially fed* design.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A substation receives its power from the transmission network, the power is stepped down with a transformer and sent to a bus from which feeders fan out in all directions across the countryside.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] These feeders carry three-phase power, and tend to follow the major streets near the substation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] As the distance from the substation grows, the fanout continues as smaller laterals spread out to cover areas missed by the feeders.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This tree-like structure grows outward from the substation, but for reliability reasons, usually contains at least one unused backup connection to a nearby substation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This connection can be enabled in case of an emergency, so that a portion of a substation's service territory can be alternatively fed by another substation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] As of 2020, the largest form of grid energy storage is dammed hydroelectricity, with both conventional hydroelectric generation as well as pumped storage hydroelectricity.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Developments in battery storage have enabled commercially viable projects to store energy during peak production and release during peak demand, and for use when production unexpectedly falls giving time for slower responding resources to be brought online.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Two alternatives to grid storage are the use of peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps and demand response to shift load to other times.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The demand, or load on an electrical grid is the total electrical power being removed by the users of the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The graph of the demand over time is called the *demand curve*.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Baseload is the minimum load on the grid over any given period, peak demand is the maximum load.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Historically, baseload was commonly met by equipment that was relatively cheap to run, that ran continuously for weeks or months at a time, but globally this is becoming less common.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The extra peak demand requirements are sometimes produced by expensive peaking plants that are generators optimised to come on-line quickly but these too are becoming less common.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] However, if the demand of electricity exceeds the capacity of a local power grid, it will cause safety issues like burning out.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Grids are designed to supply electricity to their customers at largely constant voltages.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This has to be achieved with varying demand, variable reactive loads, and even nonlinear loads, with electricity provided by generators and distribution and transmission equipment that are not perfectly reliable.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Often grids use tap changers on transformers near to the consumers to adjust the voltage and keep it within specification.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In a synchronous grid all the generators must run at the same frequency, and must stay very nearly in phase with each other and the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Generation and consumption must be balanced across the entire grid, because energy is consumed as it is produced.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For rotating generators, a local governor regulates the driving torque, maintaining almost constant rotation speed as loading changes.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Energy is stored in the immediate short term by the rotational kinetic energy of the generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Although the speed is kept largely constant, small deviations from the nominal system frequency are very important in regulating individual generators and are used as a way of assessing the equilibrium of the grid as a whole.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] When the grid is lightly loaded the grid frequency runs above the nominal frequency, and this is taken as an indication by Automatic generation control (AGC) systems across the network that generators should reduce their output.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Conversely, when the grid is heavily loaded, the frequency naturally slows, and governors adjust their generators so that more power is output (droop speed control).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] When generators have identical droop speed control settings it ensures that multiple parallel generators with the same settings share load in proportion to their rating.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In addition, there's often central control, which can change the parameters of the AGC systems over timescales of a minute or longer to further adjust the regional network flows and the operating frequency of the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For timekeeping purposes, the nominal frequency will be allowed to vary in the short term, but is adjusted to prevent line-operated clocks from gaining or losing significant time over the course of a whole 24 hour period.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Neighbouring grids that are not directly connected are almost always out-of-phase with each other.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Instead, high-voltage direct current lines or variable-frequency transformers are used, which allow two out-of-phase synchronous grids to share power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The sum of the maximum power outputs (nameplate capacity) of the generators attached to an electrical grid might be considered to be the capacity of the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] However, in practice, they are never run flat out simultaneously.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Typically, some generators are kept running at lower output powers (spinning reserve) to deal with failures as well as variation in demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In addition generators can be off-line for maintenance or other reasons, such as availability of energy inputs (fuel, water, wind, sun etc.) or pollution constraints.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Most grid codes specify that the load is shared between the generators in merit order according to their marginal cost (i.e. cheapest first) and sometimes their environmental impact.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Thus cheap electricity providers tend to be run flat out almost all the time, and the more expensive producers are only run when necessary.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A central authority is usually designated to facilitate communication and develop protocols to maintain a stable grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] For example, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation gained binding powers in the United States in 2006, and has advisory powers in the applicable parts of Canada and Mexico.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The U.S. government has also designated National Interest Electric Transmission Corridors, where it believes transmission bottlenecks have developed.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Where multiple utilities own generators connected to one electrical grid power pools are often formed which have agreements about responsibilities.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Each grid may have a system operator that is responsible for day-to-day running of one or more grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Failures are usually associated with generators or power transmission lines tripping circuit breakers due to faults leading to a loss of generation capacity for customers, or excess demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] This will often cause the frequency to reduce, and the remaining generators will react and together attempt to stabilize above the minimum.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] If that is not possible then a number of scenarios can occur.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A large failure in one part of the grid—unless quickly compensated for—can cause current to re-route itself to flow from the remaining generators to consumers over transmission lines of insufficient capacity, causing further failures.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] One downside to a widely connected grid is thus the possibility of cascading failure and widespread power outage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A *brownout* is an intentional or unintentional drop in voltage in an electrical power supply system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The reduction lasts for minutes or hours, as opposed to short-term voltage sag (or dip).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The term brownout comes from the dimming experienced by incandescent lighting when the voltage sags.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A voltage reduction may be an effect of disruption of an electrical grid, or may occasionally be imposed in an effort to reduce load and prevent a power outage, known as a blackout.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A *power outage* (also called a *power cut*, a *power out*, a *power blackout*, *power failure* or a *blackout*) is a loss of the electric power to a particular area.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Power failures can be caused by faults at power stations, damage to electric transmission lines, substations or other parts of the distribution system, a short circuit, cascading failure, fuse or circuit breaker operation, and human error.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Power failures are particularly critical at sites where the environment and public safety are at risk.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Institutions such as hospitals, sewage treatment plants, mines, shelters and the like will usually have backup power sources such as standby generators, which will automatically start up when electrical power is lost.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Other critical systems, such as telecommunication, are also required to have emergency power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The battery room of a telephone exchange usually has arrays of lead–acid batteries for backup and also a socket for connecting a generator during extended periods of outage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electrical generation and transmission systems may not always meet peak demand requirements— the greatest amount of electricity required by all utility customers within a given region.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In these situations, overall demand must be lowered, either by turning off service to some devices or cutting back the supply voltage (brownouts), in order to prevent uncontrolled service disruptions such as power outages (widespread blackouts) or equipment damage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Utilities may impose load shedding on service areas via targeted blackouts, rolling blackouts or by agreements with specific high-use industrial consumers to turn off equipment at times of system-wide peak demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A *black start* is the process of restoring an electric power station or a part of an electric grid to operation without relying on the external electric power transmission network to recover from a total or partial shutdown.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Normally, the electric power used within the plant is provided from the station's own generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] If all of the plant's main generators are shut down, station service power is provided by drawing power from the grid through the plant's transmission line.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] However, during a wide-area outage, off-site power from the grid is not available.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the absence of grid power, a so-called black start needs to be performed to bootstrap the power grid into operation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] To provide a black start, some power stations have small diesel generators, normally called the *black start diesel generator* (BSDG), which can be used to start larger generators (of several megawatts capacity), which in turn can be used to start the main power station generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Generating plants using steam turbines require station service power of up to 10% of their capacity for boiler feedwater pumps, boiler forced-draft combustion air blowers, and for fuel preparation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] It is uneconomical to provide such a large standby capacity at each station, so black-start power must be provided over designated tie lines from another station.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Often hydroelectric power plants are designated as the black-start sources to restore network interconnections.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] A hydroelectric station needs very little initial power to start (just enough to open the intake gates and provide excitation current to the generator field coils), and can put a large block of power on line very quickly to allow start-up of fossil-fuel or nuclear stations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Certain types of combustion turbine can be configured for black start, providing another option in places without suitable hydroelectric plants.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In 2017 a utility in Southern California has successfully demonstrated the use of a battery energy storage system to provide a black start, firing up a combined cycle gas turbine from an idle state.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Despite novel institutional arrangements and network designs, power delivery infrastructures is experiencing aging across the developed world.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Demand response is a grid management technique where retail or wholesale customers are requested or incentivised either electronically or manually to reduce their load.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Currently, transmission grid operators use demand response to request load reduction from major energy users such as industrial plants.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Technologies such as smart metering can encourage customers to use power when electricity is plentiful by allowing for variable pricing.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The smart grid is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Resistance to distributed generation among grid operators may encourage providers to leave the grid and instead distribute power to smaller geographies.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The Rocky Mountain Institute and other studies foresee widescale grid defection.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] However, grid defection may be less likely in places such as Germany that have greater power demands in the winter.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Early electric energy was produced near the device or service requiring that energy.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the 1880s, electricity competed with steam, hydraulics, and especially coal gas.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Coal gas was first produced on customer's premises but later evolved into gasification plants that enjoyed economies of scale.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the industrialized world, cities had networks of piped gas, used for lighting.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] But gas lamps produced poor light, wasted heat, made rooms hot and smoky, and gave off hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the 1880s electric lighting soon became advantageous compared to gas lighting.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Electric utility companies established central stations to take advantage of economies of scale and moved to centralized power generation, distribution, and system management.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] After the war of the currents was settled in favor of AC power, with long-distance power transmission it became possible to interconnect stations to balance the loads and improve load factors.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries have liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that have led to the separation of the electricity transmission business from the distribution business.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the United Kingdom, Charles Merz, of the Merz & McLellan consulting partnership, built the Neptune Bank Power Station near Newcastle upon Tyne in 1901, and by 1912 had developed into the largest integrated power system in Europe.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Merz was appointed head of a parliamentary committee and his findings led to the Williamson Report of 1918, which in turn created the Electricity (Supply) Act 1919.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The bill was the first step towards an integrated electricity system.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In 1925 the Weir Committee recommended the creation of a "national gridiron" and so the Electricity (Supply) Act 1926 created the Central Electricity Board (CEB).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The CEB standardized the nation's electricity supply and established the first synchronized AC grid, running at 132 kilovolts and 50 hertz but initially operated as regional grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] After brief overnight interconnection in 1937 they permanently and officially joined in 1938 becoming the UK National Grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In France, electrification began in the 1900s, with 700 communes in 1919, and 36,528 in 1938.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] At the same time, these close networks began to interconnect: Paris in 1907 at 12 kV, the Pyrénées in 1923 at 150 kV, and finally almost all of the country interconnected by 1938 at 220 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In 1946, the grid was the world's most dense.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] That year the state nationalised the industry, by uniting the private companies as Électricité de France.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The frequency was standardised at 50 Hz, and the 225 kV network replaced 110 kV and 120 kV.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Since 1956, service voltage has been standardised at 220/380 V, replacing the previous 127/220 V.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] During the 1970s, the 400 kV network, the new European standard, was implemented.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Starting on May 29, 1986, the end user service voltage will progressively change to 230/400 V ±10%.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the United States in the 1920s, utilities formed joint-operations to share peak load coverage and backup power.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In 1934, with the passage of the Public Utility Holding Company Act (U.S.), electric utilities were recognized as public goods of importance and were given outlined restrictions and regulatory oversight of their operations.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 1992 required transmission line owners to allow electric generation companies open access to their network and led to a restructuring of how the electric industry operated in an effort to create competition in power generation.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] No longer were electric utilities built as vertical monopolies, where generation, transmission and distribution were handled by a single company.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] Now, the three stages could be split among various companies, in an effort to provide fair access to high voltage transmission.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 allowed incentives and loan guarantees for alternative energy production and advance innovative technologies that avoided greenhouse emissions.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In China, electrification began in the 1950s.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In August 1961, the electrification of the Baoji-Fengzhou section of the Baocheng Railway was completed and delivered for operation, becoming China's first electrified railway.
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] From 1958 to 1998, China's electrified railway reached 6,200 miles (10,000 kilometres).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] As of the end of 2017, this number has reached 54,000 miles (87,000 kilometres).
[src:power-grid-systems/electrical-grid] In the current railway electrification system of China, State Grid Corporation of China—Archived 2021-12-21 at the Wayback Machine—is an important power supplier.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, the largest form of grid storage is pumped-storage hydroelectricity, with utility-scale batteries and behind-the-meter batteries coming second and third.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are well suited for short-duration storage (under 8 hours), due to their lower cost and sensitivity to degradation at high states of charge.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries and compressed air energy storage may provide storage for medium-duration.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Two forms of storage are suited for long-duration storage: green hydrogen, produced via electrolysis and thermal energy storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage is one option to making grids more flexible.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Another solution is the use of more dispatchable power plants that can change their output rapidly, for instance peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Demand response can shift load to other times and interconnections between regions can balance out fluctuations in renewables production.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The price of storage technologies typically goes down with experience.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For instance, lithium-ion batteries have been getting some 20% cheaper for each doubling of worldwide capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Systems with under 40% variable renewables need only short-term storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] At 80%, medium-duration storage becomes essential and beyond 90%, long-duration storage does too.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging, and alternative flexibility options like demand response may be more economic.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Any electrical power grid must match electricity production to consumption, both of which vary significantly over time.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Energy derived from solar and wind sources varies with the weather on time scales ranging from less than a second to weeks or longer.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Nuclear power is less flexible than fossil fuels, meaning it cannot easily match the variations in demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Thus, low-carbon electricity without storage presents special challenges to electric utilities.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is one of the three key ways to replace flexibility from fossil fuels in the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Other options are demand-side response, in which consumers change when they use electricity or how much they use.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For instance, households may have cheaper night tariffs to encourage them to use electricity at night.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Industry and commercial consumers can also change their demand to meet supply.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Improved network interconnection smooths the variations of renewables production and demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] When there is little wind in one location, another might have a surplus of production.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Expansion of transmission lines usually takes a long time.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage has a large set of roles in the electricity grid and can therefore provide many different services.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For instance, it can arbitrage by keeping it until the electricity price rises, it can help make the grid more stable, and help reduce investment into transmission infrastructure.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The type of service provided by storage depends on who manages the technology, whether the technology is based alongside generation of electricity, within the network, or at the side of consumption.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Providing short-term flexibility is a key role for energy storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, it can help with the integration of variable renewable energy, storing it when there is an oversupply of wind and solar and electricity prices are low.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] More generally, it can exploit the changes in prices of electricity over time in the wholesale market, charging when electricity is cheap and selling when it is expensive.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It can further help with grid congestion (where there is insufficient capacity on transmission lines).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Consumers can use storage to use more of their self-produced electricity (for instance from rooftop solar power).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Storage can also be used to provide essential grid services.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, storage can smooth out the variations in production, for instance for solar and wind.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It can assist in a black start after a power outage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] On the network side, these include frequency regulation (continuously) and frequency response (after unexpected changes in supply or demand).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] On the consumption side, storage can improve the quality of the delivered electricity in less stable grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Investment in storage may make some investments in the transmission and distribution network unnecessary, or may allow them to be scaled down.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Additionally, storage can ensure there is sufficient capacity to meet peak demand within the electricity grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Finally, in off-grid home systems or mini-grids, electricity storage can help provide energy access in areas that were previously not connected to the electricity grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Recent advances in artificial intelligence and machine learning allow for real-time optimization of energy storage assets.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Reinforcement learning algorithms are being explored to maximize arbitrage, manage degradation, and respond to market signals, particularly in complex and high-renewable systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Energy from sunlight or other renewable energy is converted to potential energy for storage in devices such as electric batteries.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The stored potential energy is later converted to electricity that is added to the power grid, even when the original energy source is not available.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In daytime, different renewable sources provide different amounts of power to the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] At night, energy is provided by batteries that were charged during the day when renewable energy exceeded customer demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be stored directly for a short time in capacitors, somewhat longer electrochemically in batteries, and much longer chemically (e.g. hydrogen), mechanically (e.g. pumped hydropower) or as heat.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The first pumped hydroelectricity was constructed at the end of the 19th century around the Alps in Italy, Austria, and Switzerland.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The technique rapidly expanded during the 1960s to 1980s nuclear boom, due to nuclear power's inability to quickly adapt to changes in electricity demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In the 21st century, interest in storage surged due to the rise of sustainable energy sources, which are often weather-dependent.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Commercial batteries have been available for over a century.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] However, their widespread use in the power grid is more recent, with only 1 GW available in 2013.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are the most commonly used batteries for grid applications, as of 2024, following the application of batteries in electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In comparison with EVs, grid batteries require less energy density, meaning that more emphasis can be put on costs, the ability to charge and discharge often and lifespan.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This has led to a shift towards lithium iron phosphate batteries (LFP batteries), which are cheaper and last longer than traditional lithium-ion batteries.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Costs of batteries are declining rapidly; from 2010 to 2023 costs fell by 90%.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, utility-scale systems account for two thirds of added capacity, and home applications (behind-the-meter) for one third.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are highly suited to short-duration storage (<8h) due to cost and degradation associated with high states of charge.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The electric vehicle fleet has a large overall battery capacity, which can potentially be used for grid energy storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This could be in the form of vehicle-to-grid (V2G), where cars store energy when they are not in use, or by repurposing batteries from cars at the end of the vehicle's life.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Car batteries typically range between 33 and 100 kWh; for comparison, a typical upper-middle-class household in Spain might use some 18 kWh in a day.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] By 2030, batteries in electric vehicles may be able to meet all short-term storage demand globally.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been more than 100 V2G pilot projects globally.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The effect of V2G charging on battery life can be positive or negative.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Increased cycling of batteries can lead to faster degradation, but due to better management of the state of charge and gentler charging and discharging, V2G might instead increase the lifetime of batteries.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Second-hand batteries may be useable for stationary grid storage for roughly 6 years, when their capacity drops from roughly 80% to 60% of the initial capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] LFP batteries are particularly suitable for reusing, as they degrade less than other lithium-ion batteries and recycling is less attractive as their materials are not as valuable.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In redox flow batteries, energy is stored in liquids, which are placed in two separate tanks.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] When charging or discharging, the liquids are pumped into a cell with the electrodes.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The amount of energy stored (as set by the size of the tanks) can be adjusted separately from the power output (as set by the speed of the pumps).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries have the advantages of low capital cost for charge-discharge duration over 4 h, and of long durability (many years).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries are inferior to lithium-ion batteries in terms of energy efficiency, averaging efficiencies between 60% and 75%.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium redox batteries is most commercially advanced type of flow battery, with roughly 40 companies making them as of 2022.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Sodium-ion batteries are a possible alternative to lithium-ion batteries, as they are less flammable, and use cheaper and less critical materials.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] They have a lower energy density, and possibly a shorter lifespan.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] If produced at the same scale as lithium-ion batteries, they may become 20% to 30% cheaper.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Iron-air batteries may be suitable for even longer duration storage than flow batteries (weeks), but the technology is not yet mature.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Storage in supercapacitors works well for applications where a lot of power is needed for short amount of time.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In the power grid, they are therefore mostly used in short-term frequency regulation.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Various power-to-gas and power-to-fuel technologies exist that can convert excess electricity into an easier to store chemical.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The lowest cost and most efficient one is hydrogen.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] However, it is easier to use synthetic methane with existing infrastructure and appliances, as it is very similar to natural gas.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been a number of demonstration plants where hydrogen is burned in gas turbines, either co-firing with natural gas, or on its own.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Similarly, a number of coal plants have demonstrated it is possible to co-fire ammonia when burning coal.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In 2022, there was also a small pilot to burn pure ammonia in a gas turbine.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] A portion of existing gas turbines are capable of co-firing hydrogen, which means there is, as a lower estimate, 80 GW of capacity ready to burn hydrogen.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be used as a long-term storage medium.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Green hydrogen is produced from the electrolysis of water and converted back into electricity in an internal combustion engine, or a fuel cell, with a round-trip efficiency of roughly 41%.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Together with thermal storage, it is expected to be best suited to seasonal energy storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be stored aboveground in tanks or underground in larger quantities.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Underground storage is easiest in salt caverns, but only a certain number of places have suitable geology.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Storage in porous rocks, for instance in empty gas fields and some aquifers, can store hydrogen at a larger scale, but this type of storage may have some drawbacks.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For instance, some of the hydrogen can leak or react to form hydrogen sulfide (H₂S) or methane.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be converted into ammonia in a reaction with nitrogen in the Haber-Bosch process.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia, a gas at room temperature, is more expensive to produce than hydrogen.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] However, it can be stored more cheaply than hydrogen.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Tank storage is usually done at between one and ten times atmospheric pressure and at a temperature of −30 °C (−22 °F), in liquid form.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia has multiple uses besides being an energy carrier: it is the basis for the production of many chemicals; the most common use is for fertilizer.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It can be used for power generation directly, or converted back to hydrogen first.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Alternatively, it has potential applications as a fuel in shipping.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It is possible to further convert hydrogen into methane via the Sabatier reaction, a chemical reaction which combines CO2 and H2.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] While the reaction that converts CO from gasified coal into CH4 is mature, the process to form methane out of CO2 is less so.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Efficiencies of around 80% one-way can be achieved, that is, some 20% of the energy in hydrogen is lost in the reaction.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Flywheels store energy in the form of mechanical energy.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] They are suited to supplying high levels of electricity over minutes and can also be charged rapidly.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] They have a long lifetime and can be used in settings with widely varying temperatures.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The technology is mature, but more expensive than batteries and supercapacitors and not used frequently.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, pumped-storage hydroelectricity (PSH) was the largest form of grid energy storage globally, with an installed capacity of 181 GW, surpassing the combined capacity of utility-scale and behind-the-meter battery storage, which totaled approximately 88 GW.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] PSH is particularly effective for managing daily fluctuations in energy demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] During periods of low demand, water is pumped to a higher-elevation reservoir, and during peak demand, the stored water is released to generate electricity through turbines.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The system has an efficiency rate of 75% to 85% and can quickly respond to changes in demand, typically within seconds to minutes.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] While traditional PSH systems require specific geographical conditions, alternative designs have been proposed.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] These include using deep salt caverns or constructing hollow structures on the seabed, where the ocean serves as the upper reservoir.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] However, PSH construction is often expensive, time-consuming, and can have significant environmental and social impacts on nearby communities.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Installing floating solar panels on reservoirs, can increase the efficiency of PSH systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] These panels reduce water evaporation and benefit from cooling by the water surface, which also improves their energy generation efficiency.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams with large reservoirs can also be operated to provide peak generation at times of peak demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Water is stored in the reservoir during periods of low demand and released through the plant when demand is higher.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] While technically no electricity is stored, the net effect is similar to that of pumped storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams typically offer more storage capacity than dedicated pumped-storage systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Upgrades may be needed so that these dams can respond to variable demand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For instance, additional investment may be needed in transmission lines, or additional turbines may need to be installed to increase the peak output from the dam.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As well as energy generation, they often play a role in flood defense and protection of ecosystems, recreation, and they supply water for irrigation.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This means it is not always possible to change their operation much, but even with low flexibility, they may still play an important role in responding to changes in wind and solar production.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Alternative methods that use gravity include storing energy by moving large solid masses upward against gravity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This can be achieved inside old mine shafts or in specially constructed towers where heavy weights are winched up to store energy and allowed a controlled descent to release it.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Compressed air energy storage (CAES) stores electricity by compressing air.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The compressed air is typically stored in large underground caverns.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The expanding air can be used to drive turbines, converting the energy back into electricity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As air cools when expanding, some heat needs to be added in this stage to prevent freezing.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This can be provided by a low-carbon source, or in the case of advanced CAES, by reusing the heat that is released when air is compressed.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, there are three advanced CAES projects in operation in China.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Typical efficiencies of advanced CAES are between 60% and 80%.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Another electricity storage method is to compress and cool air, turning it into liquid air, which can be stored and expanded when needed, turning a turbine to generate electricity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This is called liquid air energy storage (LAES).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The air would be cooled to temperatures of −196 °C (−320.8 °F) to become liquid.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Like with compressed air, heat is needed for the expansion step.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In the case of LAES, low-grade industrial heat can be used for this.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Energy efficiency for LAES lies between 50% and 70%.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, LAES is moving from pre-commercial to commercial.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] An alternative is the compression of CO 2 to store electricity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be directly stored thermally with a Carnot battery.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] A Carnot battery is a type of energy storage system that stores electricity in heat storage and converts the stored heat back to electricity via thermodynamic cycles (for instance, a turbine).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] While less efficient than pumped hydro or battery storage, this type of system is expected to be cheap and can provide long-duration storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] A pumped-heat electricity storage system is a Carnot battery that uses a reversible heat pump to convert the electricity into heat.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It usually stores the energy in both a hot and cold reservoir.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] To achieve decent efficiencies (>50%), the temperature ratio between the two must reach a factor of 5.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Thermal energy storage is also used in combination with concentrated solar power (CSP).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In CSP, solar energy is first converted into heat, and then either directly converted into electricity or first stored.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The energy is released when there is little or no sunshine.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This means that CSP can be used as a dispatchable (flexible) form of generation.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The energy in a CSP system can for instance be stored in molten salts or in a solid medium such as sand.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Finally, heating and cooling systems in buildings can be controlled to store thermal energy in either the building's mass or dedicated thermal storage tanks.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This thermal storage can provide load-shifting or even more complex ancillary services by increasing power consumption (charging the storage) during off-peak times and lowering power consumption (discharging the storage) during higher-priced peak times.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The levelized cost of storing electricity (LCOS) is a measure of the lifetime costs of storing electricity per MWh of electricity discharged.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It includes investment costs, but also operational costs and charging costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] It depends highly on storage type and purpose; as subsecond-scale frequency regulation, minute/hour-scale peaker plants, or day/week-scale season storage.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For power applications (for instance around ancillary services or black starts), a similar metric is the annuitized capacity cost (ACC), which measures the lifetime costs per kW.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] ACC is lowest when there are few cycles (<300) and when the discharge is less than one hour.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This is because the technology is reimbursed only when it provides spare capacity, not when it is discharged.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The cost of storage is coming down following technology-dependent experience curves, the price drop for each doubling in cumulative capacity (or experience).
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion battery prices fall rapidly: the price utilities pay for them falls 19% with each doubling of capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen production via electrolysis has a similar learning rate, but it is much more uncertain.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium-flow batteries typically get 14% cheaper for each doubling of capacity.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Pumped hydropower has not seen prices fall much with increased experience.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Before 2020, most value for storage was in providing power quality services.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Arbitrage is the service with the largest economic potential for storage applications.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] In systems with under 40% of variable renewables, only short-term storage (of less than 4 hours) is needed for integration.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] When the share of variable renewables climbs to 80%, medium-duration storage (between 4 and 16 hours, for instance compressed air) is needed.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Above 90%, large-scale long-duration storage is required.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging even then, as the costs are high.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Alternative flexibility options, such as demand response, network expansions or flexible generation (geothermal or fossil gas with carbon capture and storage) may be lower-cost.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Like with renewables, storage will "cannibalise" its own income, but even more strongly.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] That is, with more storage on the market, there is less of an opportunity to do arbitrage or deliver other services to the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] How markets are designed impacts revenue potential too.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] The income from arbitrage is quite variable between years, whereas markets that have capacity payments likely show less volatility.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is not 100% efficient, so more electricity needs to be bought than can be sold.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] This implies that if there is only a small variation in price, it may not be economical to charge and discharge.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] For instance, if the storage application is 75% efficient, the price at which the electricity is sold needs to be at least 1.33 higher than the price for which it was bought.
[src:power-grid-systems/grid-energy-storage] Typically, electricity prices vary most between day and night, which means that storage up to 8 hours has relatively high potential for profit.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Modern utility load management began about 1938, using ripple control.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] By 1948 ripple control was a practical system in wide use.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Czechoslovakia first used ripple control in the 1950s.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Early transmitters were low power, compared to modern systems, only 50 kilovolt-amps.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] They were rotating generators that fed a 1050 Hz signal into transformers attached to power distribution networks.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Early receivers were electromechanical relays.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Later, in the 1970s, transmitters with high-power semiconductors were used.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] These are more reliable because they have no moving parts.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Modern Czech systems send a digital "telegram".
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Each telegram takes about thirty seconds to send.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] There are several formats, used in different districts.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In 1972, Theodore George "Ted" Paraskevakos, while working for Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system which used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter-reading capabilities for all utilities.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] This technology was a spin-off of his patented automatic telephone line identification system, now known as caller ID.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In, 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] At the request of the Alabama Power Company, Paraskevakos developed a load-management system along with automatic meter-reading technology.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In doing so, he utilized the ability of the system to monitor the speed of the watt power meter disc and, consequently, power consumption.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] This information, along with the time of day, gave the power company the ability to instruct individual meters to manage water heater and air conditioning consumption in order to prevent peaks in usage during the high consumption portions of the day.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] For this approach, Paraskevakos was awarded multiple patents.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Since electrical energy is a form of energy that cannot be effectively stored in bulk, it must be generated, distributed, and consumed immediately.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] When the load on a system approaches the maximum generating capacity, network operators must either find additional supplies of energy or find ways to curtail the load, hence load management.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] If they are unsuccessful, the system will become unstable and blackouts can occur.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Long-term load management planning may begin by building sophisticated models to describe the physical properties of the distribution network (i.e. topology, capacity, and other characteristics of the lines), as well as the load behavior.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The analysis may include scenarios that account for weather forecasts, the predicted impact of proposed load-shed commands, estimated time-to-repair for off-line equipment, and other factors.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The utilization of load management can help a power plant achieve a higher capacity factor, a measure of average capacity utilization.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Capacity factor is a measure of the output of a power plant compared to the maximum output it could produce.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Capacity factor is often defined as *the ratio of average load to capacity* or *the ratio of average load to peak load in a period of time*.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] A higher load factor is advantageous because a power plant may be less efficient at low load factors, a high load factor means fixed costs are spread over more kWh of output (resulting in a lower price per unit of electricity), and a higher load factor means greater total output.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] If the power load factor is affected by non-availability of fuel, maintenance shut-down, unplanned breakdown, or reduced demand (as consumption pattern fluctuate throughout the day), the generation has to be adjusted, since grid energy storage is often prohibitively expensive.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Smaller utilities that buy power instead of generating their own find that they can also benefit by installing a load control system.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The penalties they must pay to the energy provider for peak usage can be significantly reduced.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Many report that a load control system can pay for itself in a single season.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] When the decision is made to curtail load, it is done so on the basis of system *reliability*.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The utility in a sense "owns the switch" and sheds loads only when the stability or reliability of the electrical distribution system is threatened.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The utility (being in the business of generating, transporting, and delivering electricity) will not disrupt their business process without due cause.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Load management, when done properly, is non-invasive, and imposes no hardship on the consumer.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The load should be shifted to off peak hours.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Demand response places the "on-off switch" in the hands of the consumer using devices such as a smart grid controlled load control switch.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] While many residential consumers pay a flat rate for electricity year-round, the utility's costs actually vary constantly, depending on demand, the distribution network, and composition of the company's electricity generation portfolio.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In a free market, the wholesale price of energy varies widely throughout the day.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Demand response programs such as those enabled by smart grids attempt to incentivize the consumer to limit usage based upon *cost* concerns.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] As costs rise during the day (as the system reaches peak capacity and more expensive peaking power plants are used), a free market economy should allow the price to rise.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] A corresponding drop in demand for the commodity should meet a fall in price.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] While this works for predictable shortages, many crises develop within seconds due to unforeseen equipment failures.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] They must be resolved in the same time-frame in order to avoid a power blackout.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Many utilities who are interested in demand response have also expressed an interest in load control capability so that they might be able to operate the "on-off switch" before price updates could be published to the consumers.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The application of load control technology continues to grow today with the sale of both radio frequency and powerline communication based systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Certain types of smart meter systems can also serve as load control systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Charge control systems can prevent the recharging of electric vehicles during peak hours.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Vehicle-to-grid systems can return electricity from an electric vehicle's batteries to the utility, or they can throttle the recharging of the vehicle batteries to a slower rate.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple control is a common form of load control, and is used in many countries around the world, including the United States, Australia, Czech Republic, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Germany, the Netherlands, and South Africa.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple control involves superimposing a higher-frequency signal (usually between 100 and 1600 Hz) onto the standard 50–60 Hz of the main power signal.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] When receiver devices attached to non-essential residential or industrial loads receive this signal, they shut down the load until the signal is disabled or another frequency signal is received.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Early implementations of ripple control occurred during World War II in various parts of the world using a system that communicates over the electrical distribution system.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Early systems used rotating generators attached to distribution networks through transformers.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple control systems are generally paired with a two- (or more) tiered pricing system, whereby electricity is more expensive during peak times (evenings) and cheaper during low-usage times (early morning).
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Affected residential devices will vary by region, but may include residential electric hot-water heaters, air conditioners, pool pumps, or crop-irrigation pumps.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In a distribution network outfitted with load control, these devices are outfitted with communicating controllers that can run a program that limits the duty cycle of the equipment under control.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Consumers are usually rewarded for participating in the load control program by paying a reduced rate for energy.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Proper load management by the utility allows them to practice load shedding to avoid rolling blackouts and reduce costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple Control is also used to turn off photovoltaic systems in case of electricity overproduction.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple control can be unpopular because sometimes devices can fail to receive the signal to turn on comfort equipment, e.g. hot water heaters or baseboard electrical heaters.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Modern electronic receivers are more reliable than old electromechanical systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Also, some modern systems repeat the telegrams to turn on comfort devices.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Also, by popular demand, many ripple control receivers have a switch to force comfort devices on.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Modern ripple controls send a digital telegram, from 30 to 180 seconds long.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Originally these were received by electromechanical relays.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Now they are often received by microprocessors.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Many systems repeat telegrams to assure that comfort devices (e.g. water heaters) are turned on.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Since the broadcast frequencies are in the range of human hearing, they often vibrate wires, filament light-bulbs or transformers in an audible way.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The telegrams follow different standards in different areas.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] For example, in the Czech Republic, different districts use "ZPA II 32S", "ZPA II 64S" and Versacom.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] ZPA II 32S sends a 2.33 second on, a 2.99 second off, then 32 one-second pulses (either on or off), with an "off time" between each pulse of one second.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] ZPA II 64S has a much shorter off time, permitting 64 pulses to be sent, or skipped.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Nearby regions use different frequencies or telegrams, to assure that telegrams operate only in the desired region.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The transformers that attach local grids to interties intentionally do not have the equipment (bridging capacitors) to pass ripple control signals into long-distance power lines.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Each data pulse of a telegram could double the number of commands, so that 32 pulses permit 2^32 distinct commands.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] However, in practice, particular pulses are linked to particular types of device or service.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] For example most ripple control systems have a telegram to set clocks in attached devices, e.g. to midnight.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Zellweger off-peak is one common brand of ripple control systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In recent years, radio-based load management (sometimes known as "**radio ripple control**") signalling systems have been introduced to replace traditional power wire ripple signalling systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Some radio-based load management systems have been criticised for lacking sufficient security measures, potentially compromising power grid security or allowing street lighting to be turned on or off.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Greater loads physically slow the rotors of a grid's synchronized generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] This causes AC mains to have a slightly reduced frequency when a grid is heavily loaded.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The reduced frequency is immediately sensible across the entire grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Inexpensive local electronics can easily and precisely measure mains frequencies and turn off sheddable loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In some cases, this feature is nearly free, e.g. if the controlling equipment (such as an electric power meter, or the thermostat in an air-conditioning system) already has a microcontroller.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Most electronic electric power meters internally measure frequency, and require only demand control relays to turn off equipment.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In other equipment, often the only needed extra equipment is a resistor divider to sense the mains cycle and a schmitt trigger (a small integrated circuit) so the microcontrollers' digital input can sense a reliable fast digital edge.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] A schmitt trigger is already standard equipment on many microcontrollers.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The main advantage over ripple control is greater customer convenience: Unreceived ripple control telegrams can cause a water heater to remain off, causing a cold shower.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Or, they can cause an airconditioner to remain off, resulting in a sweltering home.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In contrast, as the grid recovers, its frequency naturally rises to normal, so frequency-controlled load control automatically enables water heaters, air-conditioners and other comfort equipment.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The cost of equipment can be less, and there are no concerns about overlapping or unreached ripple control regions, mis-received codes, transmitter power, etc.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The main disadvantage compared to ripple control is a less fine-grained control.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] For example, a grid authority has only a limited ability to select which loads are shed.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In controlled war-time economies, this can be a substantial disadvantage.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The system was invented in PNNL in the early 21st century, and has been shown to stabilize grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The largest residential load control system in the world is found in Florida and is managed by Florida Power and Light.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] It utilizes 800,000 load control transponders (LCTs) and controls 1,000 MW of electrical power (2,000 MW in an emergency).
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] FPL has been able to avoid the construction of numerous new power plants due to their load management programs.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Since the 1950s, Australia and New Zealand have had a system of load management based on ripple control, allowing the electricity supply for domestic and commercial water storage heaters to be switched off and on, as well as allowing remote control of nightstore heaters and street lights.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple injection equipment located within each local distribution network signals to ripple control receivers at the customer's premises.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Control may either done manually by the local distribution network company in response to local outages or requests to reduce demand from the transmission system operator (i.e.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Transpower), or automatically when injection equipment detects mains frequency falling below 49.2 Hz.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Ripple control receivers are assigned to one of several ripple channels to allow the network company to only turn off supply on part of the network, and to allow staged restoration of supply to reduce the impact of a surge in demand when power is restored to water heaters after a period of time off.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Depending on the area, the consumer may have two electricity meters, one for normal supply ("Anytime") and one for the load-managed supply ("Controlled"), with Controlled supply billed at a lower rate per kilowatt-hour than Anytime supply.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] For those with load-managed supply but only a single meter, electricity is billed at the "Composite" rate, priced between Anytime and Controlled.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The Czechs have operated ripple control systems since the 1950s.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] France has an EJP tariff, which allows it to disconnect certain loads and to encourage consumers to disconnect certain loads.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] This tariff is no longer available for new clients (as of July 2009).
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The *Tempo* tariff also includes different types of days with different prices, but has been discontinued for new clients as well (as of July 2009).
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Reduced prices during nighttime are available for customers for a higher monthly fee.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The distribution system operator Westnetz and gridX piloted a load management solution.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] The solution enables the grid operator to communicate with local energy management systems and adjust the available load for EV charging in response to the state of the grid.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] Rltec in the UK in 2009 reported that domestic refrigerators are being sold fitted with their dynamic load response systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In 2011 it was announced that the Sainsbury supermarket chain will use dynamic demand technology on their heating and ventilation equipment.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] In the UK, night storage heaters are often used with a time-switched off-peak supply option - Economy 7 or Economy 10.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] There is also a programme that allows industrial loads to be disconnected using circuit breakers triggered automatically by frequency sensitive relays fitted on site.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] This operates in conjunction with Standing Reserve, a programme using diesel generators.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] These can also be remotely switched using BBC Radio 4 Longwave Radio teleswitch.
[src:power-grid-systems/load-management] SP transmission deployed Dynamic Load Management scheme in Dumfries and Galloway area using real time monitoring of embedded generation and disconnecting them, should an overload be detected on the transmission Network.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In power engineering, a **power-flow study** is a numerical analysis of the flow of electric power in an interconnected system.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] It is also known as **power-flow analysis**, **load-flow study** or **load-flow analysis**, with or without the hyphen.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] It analyzes the power systems in normal steady-state operation and may analyze the system’s capability to adequately supply the connected load.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The principal information obtained from the power-flow study is the magnitude and phase angle of the voltage at each bus, and the real power and reactive power flowing in each line.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The total system losses and individual line losses are also tabulated.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] A power-flow study usually uses simplified notations such as a one-line diagram and per-unit system.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In terms of its approach to uncertainties, power-flow study can be divided to deterministic power-flow study and uncertainty-concerned power-flow study.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Deterministic power-flow study does not take into account the uncertainties arising from both power generations and load behaviors.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] To take the uncertainties into consideration, there are several approaches that has been used such as probabilistic, possibilistic, information gap decision theory, robust optimization, and interval analysis.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Performing a power-flow study on an existing system provides insight and recommendations as to the system operation and optimization of control settings to obtain maximum capacity while minimizing the operating costs.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Power-flow studies are important for planning future expansion of power systems as well as in determining the best operation of existing systems, especially for the optimal operations of groups of generating units.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] A power-flow study is especially valuable for a system with multiple load centers, such as a refinery complex.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Commercial power systems are usually too complex to allow for hand solution of the power flow.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Special-purpose network analyzers were built between 1929 and the early 1960s to provide laboratory-scale physical models of power systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Large-scale digital computers replaced the analog methods with numerical solutions.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In addition to a power-flow study, computer programs perform related calculations such as short-circuit fault analysis, stability studies (transient and steady-state), unit commitment and economic dispatch.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In particular, some programs use linear programming to find the *optimal power flow*, the conditions which give the lowest cost per kilowatt hour delivered.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] An *alternating current power-flow model* is a model used in electrical engineering to analyze power grids.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] It provides a nonlinear system of equations which describes the energy flow through each transmission line.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The problem is non-linear because the power flow into load impedances is a function of the square of the applied voltages.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Due to nonlinearity, in many cases the analysis of large network via AC power-flow model is not feasible, and a linear (but less accurate) DC power-flow model is used instead.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Usually, analysis of a three-phase power system is simplified by assuming balanced loading of all three phases.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Sinusoidal steady-state operation is assumed, with no transient changes in power flow or voltage due to load or generation changes, meaning all current and voltage waveforms are sinusoidal with no DC offset and have the same constant frequency.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The previous assumption is the same as assuming the power system is linear time-invariant (even though the system of equations is nonlinear), driven by sinusoidal sources of same frequency, and operating in steady-state, which allows to use phasor analysis, another simplification.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] A further simplification is to use the per-unit system to represent all voltages, power flows, and impedances, scaling the actual target system values to some convenient base.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] A system one-line diagram is the basis to build a mathematical model of the generators, loads, buses, and transmission lines of the system, and their electrical impedances and ratings.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] DC power flow (also known as DC load flow, or DCLF) gives estimations of lines power flows on AC power systems.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Despite the name, DC power flow is not an analysis on direct current, but rather on alternating current; the name comes from the linearity of the analysis, which resembles analysis on direct current.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] DC power flow looks only at active power flows and neglects reactive power flows.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] This method is non-iterative and absolutely convergent but less accurate than AC Load Flow solutions.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] DC power flow is used wherever repetitive and fast load flow estimations are required.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The goal of a power-flow study is to obtain complete voltage angles and magnitude information for each bus in a power system for specified load and generator real power and voltage conditions.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Once this information is known, real and reactive power flow on each branch as well as generator reactive power output can be analytically determined.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Due to the nonlinear nature of this problem, numerical methods are employed to obtain a solution that is within an acceptable tolerance.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The solution to the power-flow problem begins with identifying the known and unknown variables in the system.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The known and unknown variables are dependent on the type of bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] A bus without any generators connected to it is called a Load Bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] With one exception, a bus with at least one generator connected to it is called a Generator Bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The exception is one arbitrarily-selected bus that has a generator.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] This bus is referred to as the slack bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In the power-flow problem, it is assumed that the real power $P_{D}$ and reactive power $Q_{D}$ at each Load Bus are known.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] For this reason, Load Buses are also known as PQ Buses.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] For Generator Buses, it is assumed that the real power generated $P_{G}$ and the voltage magnitude $|V|$ is known.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] For the Slack Bus, it is assumed that the voltage magnitude $|V|$ and voltage phase $\theta$ are known.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Therefore, for each Load Bus, both the voltage magnitude and angle are unknown and must be solved for; for each Generator Bus, the voltage angle must be solved for; there are no variables that must be solved for the Slack Bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In a system with N buses and R generators, there are then $2(N-1)-(R-1)$ unknowns.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In order to solve for the $2(N-1)-(R-1)$ unknowns, there must be $2(N-1)-(R-1)$ equations that do not introduce any new unknown variables.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The possible equations to use are power balance equations, which can be written for real and reactive power for each bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] where $Q_{i}$ is the net reactive power injected at bus *i*.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Equations included are the real and reactive power balance equations for each Load Bus and the real power balance equation for each Generator Bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Only the real power balance equation is written for a Generator Bus because the net reactive power injected is assumed to be unknown and therefore including the reactive power balance equation would result in an additional unknown variable.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] For similar reasons, there are no equations written for the Slack Bus.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] In many transmission systems, the impedance of the power network lines is primarily inductive, i.e. the phase angles of the power lines impedance are usually relatively large and very close to 90 degrees.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] There is thus a strong coupling between real power and voltage angle, and between reactive power and voltage magnitude, while the coupling between real power and voltage magnitude, as well as reactive power and voltage angle, is weak.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] As a result, real power is usually transmitted from the bus with higher voltage angle to the bus with lower voltage angle, and reactive power is usually transmitted from the bus with higher voltage magnitude to the bus with lower voltage magnitude.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] However, this approximation does not hold when the phase angle of the power line impedance is relatively small.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] There are several different methods of solving the resulting nonlinear system of equations.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The most popular is a variation of the Newton–Raphson method.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The Newton-Raphson method is an iterative method which begins with initial guesses of all unknown variables (voltage magnitude and angles at Load Buses and voltage angles at Generator Buses).
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Next, a Taylor Series is written, with the higher order terms ignored, for each of the power balance equations included in the system of equations.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] and J is a matrix of partial derivatives known as a Jacobian: $J={\begin{bmatrix}{\dfrac {\partial \Delta P}{\partial \theta }}&{\dfrac {\partial \Delta P}{\partial |V|}}\\{\dfrac {\partial \Delta Q}{\partial \theta }}&{\dfrac {\partial \Delta Q}{\partial |V|}}\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] The process continues until a stopping condition is met.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] A common stopping condition is to terminate if the norm of the mismatch equations is below a specified tolerance.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Solve the power balance equations using the most recent voltage angle and magnitude values.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-flow-study] Check the stopping conditions, if met then terminate, else go to step 2.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The **protection devices** are used to protect the power systems from faults by detecting the faults and taking *action* ("**tripping**").
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Anderson distinguishes the *reactionary devices*, like protective relays, that "clear" a fault by isolating it from the rest of system and *safeguard devices* that address the source of the hazard (for example, an emergency core cooling system of a nuclear reactor).
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] As a discipline, power system protection mostly deals with the reactionary devices.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] With the exception of the breaker, the components of the protective device are frequently deployed in a redundant fashion.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The objective of a protection scheme is to keep the power system stable by isolating only the components that are under fault, whilst leaving as much of the network as possible in operation, thus minimizing the loss of load.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] This property of the protection system is called *selectivity*.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] To achieve selectivity, the power system is subdivided into *protective zones*, each containing a power system component (generator, bus, transformer, transmission or distribution line, motor) that should be protected.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Each zone has its own protection device(s) and provides sensitivity to faults within its boundaries.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] If a fault were to occur in a given zone, necessary actions will be executed to isolate that zone from the entire system (all circuit breakers in a given zone with a fault will open in order to isolate the fault).
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The boundaries of zones overlap to leave no part of grid without protection, overlapped regions usually surround circuit breakers with two sets of instrument transformers and relays for each circuit breaker.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The overlapping regions of sensitivity have a drawback of multiple relays possibly tripping when the fault is in the overlapped area.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] For example, unless special arrangements are made, a short circuit above the relay A, but still within the blue zone on the diagram, might cause overcurrent conditions in relays A, C, and D and cause them to trip, with the two latter trips being redundant.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] This can be avoided by using specialized relays (distance or directional ones) or by coordinating the relay actions using a communication channel ("pilot").
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] In any case, overlapped regions are designed to be as small as possible such that when a fault occurs in an overlap region and the two zones which encompass the fault are isolated, the sector of the power system.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The power protection system needs to be resilient to its own malfunctions.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Thus it includes backup protection devices.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] For example if the fault is in the top left red zone, but outside the blue zone, it is expected to be handled by the "primary" relay A.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] If the relay A malfunctions and cannot clear the fault, the *backup relays* C and D in the adjacent (blue) zone will trip.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] This can be arranged without coordination (for example, the delay setting of C and D can be higher so they do not act if A succeeds in clearing the fault) or through coordination via a pilot.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The term *local backup* is used when the backup relays are within the same zone as the "primary" one being duplicated.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Local back-up protection, like the primary protective device, will isolate the elements of the plant affected by the fault to clear the latter.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Adjacent-zone ("remote") back-up protection will generally isolate both the affected and unaffected items of plant to clear the fault.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Many pieces of the grid equipment can develop internal problems.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] For these devices, the faults can be classified into *internal* and *external*.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] As an example of the internal fault, a transformer might develop overpressure inside its containment vessel with the root cause (for example, local overheating) not triggering any other alarms.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] For the same transformer, an overload condition would represent an external fault.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] In the 21st century a lot of testing for abnormal conditions is performed by multifunctional numerical relays that use computers for calculations.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Individual measurements use cryptic identifiers from the ANSI device numbers list, like "50" for the "Instantaneous Overcurrent Relay" or "87L" for the "Segregated Line Current Differential".
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] High-voltage transmission lines typically form a mesh-like grid, so the current might be flowing into the fault from either direction, making the non-directional relays mostly unsuitable for protection, so the distance and pilot relays are typically used.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The use of directional relays is not always possible.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] In a grounded neutral transmission line, the phase relays might detect and clear a ground fault.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] However, since almost all faults on high-voltage lines are of the one-phase-to-ground variety, specialized ground relays are used for quick reaction.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] These relay utilize the zero-sequence current for detection.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] During the normal operation, the zero-sequence current is very small, so a high current value that depends on the network configuration, not on the (varying) load, is a convenient and reliable indicator of a ground fault.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Generators are expensive and complex pieces of the grid equipment, thus the larger machines use tens of types of protection devices.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Practically every generator has the stator protection, usually using differential relays.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The internal failures of generators are unusual, so the protective relays trips are very rare.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Not only the transformers are expensive, but it might take a long time to replace a failed large transformer.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Electrical protection of a transformer mostly uses the differential relays.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] This protection can be combined with the one of the busbar or generator.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] The low-voltage network generally relies upon fuses or low-voltage circuit breakers to remove both overload and earth faults.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Disturbance-monitoring equipment (DME) monitors and records system data pertaining to a fault.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Protection engineers define dependability as the tendency of the protection system to operate correctly for in-zone faults.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] They define security as the tendency not to operate for out-of-zone faults.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Both dependability and security are reliability issues.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Fault tree analysis is one tool with which a protection engineer can compare the relative reliability of proposed protection schemes.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Quantifying protection reliability is important for making the best decisions on improving a protection system, managing dependability versus security tradeoffs, and getting the best results for the least money.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] A quantitative understanding is essential in the competitive utility industry.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] There are two aspects of reliable operation of protection systems: dependability and security.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Dependability is the ability of the protection system to operate when called upon to remove a faulted element from the power system.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Security is the ability of the protection system to restrain itself from operating during an external fault.
[src:power-grid-systems/power-system-protection] Choosing the appropriate balance between security and dependability in designing the protection system requires engineering judgement and varies on a case-by-case basis.
